### 2. Long-Term ANS Responses to Solar and Geomagnetic Changes

**Alabdulgader et al. (2018)** - "Long-Term Study of Heart Rate Variability Responses to Changes in the Solar and Geomagnetic Environment"
- **Journal**: Scientific Reports (Nature)
- **DOI**: 10.1038/s41598-018-20932-x
- **URL**: https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-018-20932-x
- **Zotero Key**: FD4WRRK8

**Study Design**:
- 5-month longitudinal study
- 16 participants
- 72 consecutive hours of HRV recording each week
- Multivariate linear regression with Bonferroni corrections

**Key Findings**:
- Daily ANS activity responds to changes in geomagnetic and solar activity during normal undisturbed periods
- **Increased solar wind intensity** → increased heart rate (biological stress response)
- **Increased cosmic rays, solar radio flux, and Schumann resonance** → increased HRV and parasympathetic activity
- Responses initiated at different times after environmental changes
- Effects persist over varying time periods
- Individual sensitivity, health status, and self-regulation capacity affect degree of response

