## Executive Summary

This comprehensive literature review examines the bidirectional relationship between Earth's geomagnetic environment and human cardiovascular autonomic regulation, specifically through heart rate variability (HRV) metrics. Drawing from epidemiological studies, experimental research, and physiological investigations spanning two decades, the evidence consistently demonstrates that geomagnetic disturbances (GMDs) driven by solar activity influence autonomic nervous system function and cardiovascular health outcomes. The review synthesizes findings from multiple research domains including heliobiology, environmental health, cardiology, and space medicine.

